ns":["Renal osteodystrophy","Polycythaemia","Hypocalcaemia only","Metabolic alkalosis","Decreased blood pressure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAs kidney function declines in CKD, multiple systemic complications develop. \u003Cstrong\u003ERenal osteodystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to secondary hyperparathyroidism from phosphate retention and decreased vitamin D activation\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other answers are incorrect: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycythaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - CKD causes anaemia due to decreased erythropoietin production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs but is accompanied by hyperphosphataemia and other mineral disturbances\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - CKD typically causes metabolic acidosis due to decreased acid excretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - hypertension is common in CKD due to fluid retention and activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic kidney disease leads to multiple systemic complications including bone disease, anaemia, cardiovascular disease, and metabolic derangements","Secondary hyperparathyroidism in chronic kidney disease occurs due to phosphate retention and reduced vitamin D activation"],"references":["Chen TK, Knicely DH, Grams ME. Chronic Kidney Disease Diagnosis and Management: A Review. JAMA. 2019 Oct 1;322(13):1294-1304. doi: 10.1001/jama.2019.14745. PMID: 31573641; PMCID: PMC7015670.","Vaidya SR, Aeddula NR. Chronic Kidney Disease. [Updated 2024 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535404/","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69908"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15106"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69908"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-16T21:28:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-16T21:29:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"